"Gjerdrum C., Vallée A.M.J., St. Clair C.C., Bertram D.F., Ryder J.L., Blackburn G.S.","Tufted puffin reproduction reveals ocean climate variability",2003,"Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences of the United States of America","100","16",,"9377","9382",,,10.1073/pnas.1133383100,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0041923677&partnerID=40&md5=776a5cc9854b26f023e2061326ba7057","Centre for Wildlife Ecology, Department of Biological Sciences, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC V5A 1S6, Canada; Department of Animal Science, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z2, Canada; Department of Biological Sciences, University of Alberta, Edmonton, Alta. T6G 2E9, Canada; Environment Canada, Canadian Wildlife Service, Pacific and Yukon Region, RR1 5421 Robertson Road, Delta, BC V4K 3N2, Canada; Dept. of Ecol. and Evol. Biology, University of Connecticut, Storrs, CT 06269, United States; Environment Canada, Canadian Wildlife Service, c/o Institute of Ocean Sciences, P.O. Box 6000, Sidney, BC V8L 4B2, Canada","Gjerdrum, C., Centre for Wildlife Ecology, Department of Biological Sciences, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC V5A 1S6, Canada, Dept. of Ecol. and Evol. Biology, University of Connecticut, Storrs, CT 06269, United States; Vallée, A.M.J., Department of Animal Science, University of British Columbia, Vancouver, BC V6T 1Z2, Canada; St. Clair, C.C., Centre for Wildlife Ecology, Department of Biological Sciences, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC V5A 1S6, Canada, Department of Biological Sciences, University of Alberta, Edmonton, Alta. T6G 2E9, Canada; Bertram, D.F., Centre for Wildlife Ecology, Department of Biological Sciences, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC V5A 1S6, Canada, Environment Canada, Canadian Wildlife Service, Pacific and Yukon Region, RR1 5421 Robertson Road, Delta, BC V4K 3N2, Canada, Environment Canada, Canadian Wildlife Service, c/o Institute of Ocean Sciences, P.O. Box 6000, Sidney, BC V8L 4B2, Canada; Ryder, J.L., Centre for Wildlife Ecology, Department of Biological Sciences, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC V5A 1S6, Canada; Blackburn, G.S., Centre for Wildlife Ecology, Department of Biological Sciences, Simon Fraser University, Burnaby, BC V5A 1S6, Canada","Anomalously warm sea-surface temperatures (SSTs) are associated with interannual and decadal variability as well as with long-term climate changes indicative of global warming. Such oscillations could precipitate changes in a variety of oceanic processes to affect marine species worldwide. As global temperatures continue to rise, it will be critically important to be able to predict the effects of such changes on species' abundance, distribution, and ecological relationships so as to identify vulnerable populations. Off the coast of British Columbia, warm SSTs have persisted through the last two decades. Based on 16 years of reproductive data collected between 1975 and 2002, we show that the extreme variation in reproductive performance exhibited by tufted puffins (Fratercula cirrhata) was related to changes in SST both within and among seasons. Especially warm SSTs corresponded with drastically decreased growth rates and fledging success of puffin nestlings. Puffins may partially compensate for within-season changes associated with SST by adjusting their breeding phenology, yet our data also suggest that they are highly vulnerable to the effects of climate change at this site and may serve as a valuable indicator of biological change in the North Pacific. Further and prolonged increases in ocean temperature could make Triangle Island, which contains the largest tufted puffin colony in Canada, unsuitable as a breeding site for this species.",,"article; Canada; climate change; environmental impact assessment; Fratercula cirrhata; greenhouse effect; nonhuman; ocean environment; oscillation; predator; prediction; priority journal; reproduction; sea pollution; sea surface temperature; seabird; Animals; Birds; Climate; Ecology; Oceans and Seas; Reproduction; Seasons; Sexual Behavior; Temperature; Time Factors; Animalia; Fratercula; Fratercula cirrhata; Laridae",,,,,,"McGowan, J.A., Cayan, D.R., Dorman, L.M., (1998) Science, 281, pp. 210-217; Trenberth, K.E., Hurrell, J.W., (1994) Clim. Dyn., 9, pp. 303-319; Hallowed, A.B., Hare, S.R., Wooster, W.S., (2001) Prog. Oceanogr., 49, pp. 257-282; Roemmich, D., McGowan, J.A., (1995) Science, 267, pp. 1324-1326; Anderson, P.J., Piatt, J.F., (1999) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 189, pp. 117-123; Mackas, D.L., Thompson, R.E., Galbraith, M., (2001) Can. J. Fish. Aquat. Sci., 58, pp. 685-702; McFarlane, G.A., Beamish, R.J., (2001) Prog. Oceanogr., 49, pp. 151-165; Veit, R.R., McGowan, J.A., Ainley, D.G., Wahls, T., Pyle, P., (1997) Global Change Biol., 3, pp. 23-28; Agler, B.A., Kendall, S.J., Irons, D.B., Klosiewski, S.P., (1999) Waterbirds, 22, pp. 98-103; Ainley, D.G., Divoky, G.J., (2001) Encyclopedia of Ocean Sciences, pp. 2669-2677. , eds. Steele, J. H., Thorpe, S. A. & Turekian, K. K. (Academic, San Diego); Watson, R.T., (2001) Climate Change 2001: Synthesis Report: Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, , Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U.K; Ware, D.M., McFarlane, G.A., (1989) Effects of Ocean Variability on Recruitment and an Evaluation of Parameters Used in Stock Assessment Models, pp. 359-379. , Canadian Special Publication of Fisheries and Aquatic Sciences 108, eds. Beamish, R. J. & McFarlane, G. A. (Dept. of Fisheries and Oceans, Ottawa); Ainley, D.G., Spear, L.B., Allen, S.G., (1996) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 137, pp. 1-10; Ainley, D.G., Sydeman, W.J., Norton, J., (1995) Mar. Ecol. Prog. Ser., 118, pp. 69-79; Cairns, D.K., (1987) Biol. Oceanogr., 5, pp. 261-271; Montevecchi, W.A., (1993) Birds as Monitors of Environmental Change, pp. 217-265. , eds. Furness, R. W. & Greenwood, J. J. D. (Chapman & Hall, London); Gaston, A.J., Smith, J.L., (2001) Can. J. Zool., 79, pp. 1735-1742; Bertram, D.F., Jones, I